{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Human evaluation involves human judges assessing the quality of the machine translation output.",
    "The two main early methods used were ALPAC and DARPA [21].",
    "ALPAC focuses on intelligibility (translation understandable) and fidelity (how much original information is retained).",
    "DARPA examines adequacy (how much information is conveyed), fluency (is the output grammatical), and informativeness (does it provide information about the system's abilities).",
    "However, new advanced methods, including the Multidimensional Quality Metrics (MQM) framework [35], which offers a versatile and effective evaluation framework for assessing MT quality and transcending language barriers, have gained traction among researchers owing to its adaptability and merits. 2."
  ],
